The royal family was elevated to the throne following a referendum in 1953, when the population decided that the monarch must be elected by the people. The throne holder who actively participated in WWII is still respected and loved, in spite of the fact that he has not created anything new and his descendants, as is typical for the royal families, have done nothing but bring kids and had royal wedding parties.

If we compare what we said above with how it was in other world powers:

The president of a republic becomes president through elections. His actions may run-century or may be forgotten the day after, as is the case with some of the creatures holding the post in post-Soviet territory.
Naturally, the president of a republic does not have the ability to create the policies of the country – he must listen to the voice of the people and the parliament through which the law passes. A president is voted in. A person from the country may be elected, but policy is established through the connection between the people and the parliament.

By Creating That Connection among the People, Repression Turns into Freedom
